<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-635-900  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 635 900.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  August 16 1989 n113 p13(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft plans levels of BASIC within Windows.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (product enhancement)OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (productenhancement).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentBASICProgramming LanguagesMacrosProgram Development ToolsSoftware MigrationPlanning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft has given details of its plans for new versions of BASIC.andP;  Theseinclude configuring the language as a Windows development language and as acommon macro language.andM;According to Owen Carton, language product manager for Microsoft UK, &quot;We'relooking to have several hierarchies of BASIC in Windows and PresentationManager.andP;  The lowest level is within an application where the controllanguage supplied with, say, a database will be a superset of BASIC withsupport for DDE (Dynamic Data Exchange) and SQL, and dialogue box support.andM;&quot;Above that you'd assume that we will port things like Quickbasic intoWindows, so you'd have a development language in Windows for developingWindows applications.andP;  Currently you do that with C from a character-basedworld.andP;  But we're looking to get Windows development actually in Windows.andM;&quot;Coming on from that, is sharing objects across multiple applications.andO;That's quite a ways out and needs an object-oriented file system, and we'd dothat concurrently with our move to object-oriented Me systems under OS/2 -and then we'd see shared objects and control languages able to share thoseobjects.&quot;andM;He added that DDE is available in the current version of Excel and wouldbecome useful when implemented on a second Windows application.andM;David Svendon, managing director of Microsoft UK, said, &quot;We will have BASICas a macro tool; an extended or hyper BASIC which will be part of some of ourapplications as a means of programmability within die application and acrossit.andM;&quot;This latter function means that you need a Windows-type of interface andconnectivity to make that applicable,&quot; he added.andO;</TEXT></DOC>